Hierarchical Distributed Model Predictive Control for Provably Safe Adaptive Reentry Thermal Protection: ISS Guarantees, Event‑Triggered Coordination, and Thermodynamic Optimality

Ouadi Maakoul
Avril 2026

---

Abstract

Reusable launch vehicles demand thermal protection systems (TPS) that are not only lightweight and durable but also capable of adapting to off‑nominal reentry conditions, localized damage, and resource constraints. Passive TPS, such as the silica tiles on SpaceX Starship, are inherently non‑adaptive and must be over‑designed for worst‑case heating, leading to mass penalties and vulnerability to damage. Recent advances in active cooling—transpiration through additively manufactured porous silicon carbide, microchannel liquid cooling, and variable‑emissivity coatings—offer unprecedented control over local heat fluxes, yet no integrated framework exists to coordinate these actuators across hundreds of tiles.

This thesis presents a hierarchical distributed model predictive control (DMPC) architecture that coordinates an array of active thermal protection tiles to achieve global safety, resource efficiency, and structural longevity. The key theoretical contributions are:

1. A unifying safety–optimality principle proving that the proposed DMPC policy is the unique control class that simultaneously guarantees safety invariance (via Hamilton–Jacobi–Isaacs reachability), input‑to‑state stability (ISS) under bounded disturbances, finite‑time convergence to a safe temperature set, and Pareto‑optimal trade‑offs among peak temperature, energy consumption, and entropy production.
2. A distributed MPC formulation solved with Nesterov‑accelerated alternating direction method of multipliers (ADMM), achieving O(1/k^2) convergence and real‑time feasibility on radiation‑hardened microcontrollers.
3. An event‑triggered communication protocol with provable minimum inter‑event time, reducing network load and providing robustness against plasma blackout; a switched ISS result ensures stability even under intermittent communication loss.
4. Rigorous stability analyses: input‑to‑state stability for the interconnected multi‑agent system, string stability to prevent disturbance amplification along the vehicle, and a finite‑time stability proof derived directly from actuator saturation and cooling dominance.
5. A thermodynamic Pareto‑optimality theorem establishing that no admissible distributed policy can improve peak temperature, energy consumption, or entropy production without worsening at least one of the others.
6. A coolant feasibility necessity proposition showing that non‑adaptive cooling policies require infeasible coolant masses, thereby demonstrating that distributed adaptive control is not merely advantageous but indispensable for practical reusable launch vehicles.
7. A thermal Laplacian dynamics interpretation proving that the consensus term in DMPC directly minimizes thermal gradient energy, acting as an optimal diffusion process.
8. A modular, fault‑tolerant hardware architecture mapping the framework to space‑qualified microcontrollers, redundant mesh networking, and additively manufactured porous SiC tiles with embedded sensors and actuators.

The theoretical results are self‑contained and mathematically rigorous, providing a foundation for future experimental validation in plasma wind tunnels and flight demonstrations. This work establishes that safe, reusable orbital reentry is fundamentally a distributed control problem, shifting the paradigm from passive material resistance to active physical‑control co‑design.

Keywords: Distributed model predictive control, reentry thermal protection, input‑to‑state stability, finite‑time stability, event‑triggered communication, ADMM, Hamilton–Jacobi–Isaacs reachability, thermodynamic optimality, reusable launch vehicles.

