2.2 Active Cooling Technologies

Active cooling technologies use a working fluid or electrically controlled surface properties to modulate heat transfer. Recent advances have made several technologies viable for integration into TPS.

2.2.1 Transpiration Cooling

Transpiration cooling forces a gas (e.g., helium, nitrogen, or water vapor) through a porous material, forming a protective film that absorbs heat and reduces convective heating. The cooling effectiveness depends on the mass flow rate, the coolant properties, and the porosity of the material.

Recent breakthroughs: Additively manufactured porous silicon carbide (SiC) with tailored porosity has been developed by Texas A&M University and Canopy Aerospace under AFRL contracts. Plasma wind‑tunnel tests in 2025 demonstrated survival at heat fluxes exceeding 1\,\text{MW/m}^2 with transpiration mass flow rates of 0.1–1\,\text{kg/s/m}^2. A hypersonic flight demonstration is planned for 2027.

Modeling: The cooling flux can be expressed as

q_{\text{trans}} = \dot{m} \Delta h,

where \dot{m} is the mass flow rate per unit area and \Delta h is the enthalpy of vaporization (for phase‑change coolants) or the sensible heat capacity (for gases).

2.2.2 Microchannel Cooling

Microchannel cooling embeds micro‑scale channels (typical hydraulic diameter 500\,\mu\text{m}) into the TPS material. A liquid coolant (e.g., water, ammonia, or a fluorinated fluid) circulates through the channels, absorbing heat via forced convection.

Advantages: High heat transfer coefficients, compact integration, and compatibility with ceramic matrix composites. Microchannel cooling is well established in high‑power electronics and has been proposed for hypersonic leading edges.

Challenges: Pressure drop management, integration into ceramic composites, and ensuring leak‑tightness under thermal cycling.

The cooling flux can be modeled as

q_{\text{micro}} = h_{\text{eff}} (T_{\text{wall}} - T_{\text{coolant}}),

where h_{\text{eff}} is the effective heat transfer coefficient, which depends on the coolant flow rate and channel geometry.

2.2.3 Variable‑Emissivity Coatings (VEMs)

Variable‑emissivity coatings based on vanadium dioxide (\text{VO}_2) undergo a metal‑insulator transition around 340\,\text{K}, causing a sharp change in emissivity from approximately 0.2 to 0.8. Electrochromic variants allow active control via an applied voltage, enabling on‑demand radiative cooling.

Recent progress: The SPIRRAL program (TFAWS 2025) reported successful calorimetric testing of \text{VO}_2‑based VEMs in simulated reentry environments. Emissivity switching was demonstrated with response times on the order of seconds.

The radiative cooling flux is

q_{\text{rad}} = \epsilon(T) \sigma (T^4 - T_\infty^4),

where \epsilon(T) can be controlled between \epsilon_{\min} and \epsilon_{\max} via voltage or temperature.

2.2.4 Actuator Integration

Each of these technologies can be integrated into a single tile: transpiration through the porous structure, microchannel cooling through embedded channels, and VEM as a surface coating. The control inputs are:

· u_i^{(1)}: transpiration mass flow rate (kg/s/m²)
· u_i^{(2)}: microchannel coolant mass flow rate (kg/s/m²)
· u_i^{(3)}: emissivity setpoint (dimensionless, between 0.2 and 0.8)

These inputs are constrained by physical limits: 0 \le u_i^{(1)} \le u_{\max}^{(1)}, 0 \le u_i^{(2)} \le u_{\max}^{(2)}, and \epsilon_{\min} \le u_i^{(3)} \le \epsilon_{\max}. The microchannel flow also has a lower bound due to pump cavitation or minimum flow requirements.

