Chapter 3: Problem Formulation

This chapter derives the mathematical model of the thermal protection system, formulates it as a networked multi‑agent system, and defines the control objectives and constraints.

---

3.1 Continuous Thermal Dynamics

Let \Omega \subset \mathbb{R}^2 be the spacecraft surface, parameterized by coordinates (x,y). The temperature field T(x,y,t) satisfies the nonlinear heat equation with internal heat sources, cooling, and radiation:

\rho c_p \frac{\partial T}{\partial t} = \nabla \cdot \big( k(T) \nabla T \big) + q_{\text{aero}}(x,y,t) - \nabla \cdot q_{\text{cool}}(x,y,t) - q_{\text{rad}}(x,y,t)

where:

· \rho is the density of the TPS material (kg/m³),
· c_p is the specific heat capacity at constant pressure (J/(kg·K)),
· k(T) is the temperature‑dependent thermal conductivity (W/(m·K)),
· q_{\text{aero}}(x,y,t) is the aerodynamic + plasma heat flux (W/m²), considered an external disturbance,
· q_{\text{cool}}(x,y,t) is the active cooling flux vector (W/m²), which may have components in the tangential direction (for microchannel flow) and normal direction (for transpiration),
· q_{\text{rad}}(x,y,t) = \epsilon(x,y,t) \sigma (T^4 - T_\infty^4) is the radiative cooling flux (W/m²), with \epsilon the emissivity (control input) and \sigma = 5.67\times 10^{-8}\,\text{W/(m}^2\text{K}^4) the Stefan–Boltzmann constant.

Boundary conditions: The edges of the TPS array are assumed insulated (no heat transfer to adjacent structures), except for the surface exposed to the flow, which is subject to q_{\text{aero}} and q_{\text{rad}}.

Remark 3.1. The aerodynamic heat flux q_{\text{aero}} is a function of the freestream conditions, the vehicle attitude, and the local flow field. It can be expressed as

q_{\text{aero}} = \frac{1}{2} \rho_\infty V_\infty^3 C_H,

where \rho_\infty is the freestream density, V_\infty the velocity, and C_H the Stanton number (a function of Mach number, Reynolds number, and surface temperature). During reentry, q_{\text{aero}} varies rapidly with time and spatial location, with the stagnation point experiencing the highest heat flux.

---

3.2 Discretization as a Networked System

We discretize \Omega into N finite‑volume cells, each associated with an agent i. Let V_i be the volume of cell i, A_i the surface area exposed to the flow, and \mathcal{N}_i the set of neighboring cells (based on adjacency in the mesh). For simplicity, we assume a structured grid, so each cell has up to four neighbors (north, south, east, west). The communication graph \mathcal{G} = (\mathcal{V},\mathcal{E}) is assumed undirected and connected during nominal operation.

3.2.1 Finite‑Volume Discretization

Integrating the heat equation over cell i and applying the divergence theorem yields:

\rho c_p V_i \frac{dT_i}{dt} = \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} \int_{\Gamma_{ij}} k(T) \nabla T \cdot \mathbf{n}_{ij} \, d\Gamma + A_i q_{\text{aero},i} - \int_{\partial V_i} q_{\text{cool}} \cdot \mathbf{n} \, d\Gamma - A_i q_{\text{rad},i},

where \Gamma_{ij} is the interface between cells i and j, and \mathbf{n}_{ij} is the unit normal pointing from i to j.

We approximate the conductive heat flux using a two‑point flux approximation:

\int_{\Gamma_{ij}} k(T) \nabla T \cdot \mathbf{n}_{ij} \, d\Gamma \approx \frac{k_{ij}(T_i,T_j)}{d_{ij}} A_{ij} (T_j - T_i),

where d_{ij} is the distance between cell centers, A_{ij} is the interface area, and k_{ij} is an effective thermal conductivity (e.g., harmonic mean of k(T_i) and k(T_j)).

Similarly, the cooling flux integral is approximated as

\int_{\partial V_i} q_{\text{cool}} \cdot \mathbf{n} \, d\Gamma \approx A_i q_{\text{cool},i},

where q_{\text{cool},i} is the net cooling flux (positive outward) contributed by the actuators within cell i. For a tile with transpiration and microchannel cooling, we have

q_{\text{cool},i} = q_{\text{trans},i} + q_{\text{micro},i},

with

q_{\text{trans},i} = \dot{m}_i \Delta h, \qquad q_{\text{micro},i} = h_{\text{eff},i} (T_i - T_{\text{coolant},i}),

and \dot{m}_i is the transpiration mass flow rate per unit area, \Delta h the enthalpy change of the coolant, and h_{\text{eff},i} the effective heat transfer coefficient for microchannel cooling.

3.2.2 Compact Notation

Define the following quantities:

· T_i: temperature of cell i (K)
· u_i^{(1)} = \dot{m}_i: transpiration mass flow rate (kg/s/m²)
· u_i^{(2)} = \dot{m}_{\text{micro},i}: microchannel mass flow rate (kg/s/m²)
· u_i^{(3)} = \epsilon_i: emissivity (dimensionless)
· w_i: lumped disturbance including q_{\text{aero},i} and linearization errors.

The semi‑discrete heat equation becomes:

\rho c_p V_i \dot{T}_i = \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \frac{k_{ij} A_{ij}}{d_{ij}} (T_j - T_i) + A_i q_{\text{aero},i} - A_i q_{\text{cool},i} - A_i \epsilon_i \sigma (T_i^4 - T_\infty^4).

For convenience, define the effective conductances

k_{ij}^{\text{eff}} = \frac{k_{ij} A_{ij}}{\rho c_p V_i d_{ij}}.

Then

\dot{T}_i = \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} k_{ij}^{\text{eff}} (T_j - T_i) + \frac{A_i}{\rho c_p V_i} q_{\text{aero},i} - \frac{A_i}{\rho c_p V_i} q_{\text{cool},i} - \frac{A_i \epsilon_i \sigma}{\rho c_p V_i} (T_i^4 - T_\infty^4).
\tag{3.1}

---

3.3 Second‑Order Agent Dynamics

To incorporate thermal inertia and facilitate control design, we introduce the state vector \mathbf{x}_i = [T_i,\; \dot{T}_i]^\top. Differentiating (3.1) with respect to time yields an expression for \ddot{T}_i. This involves derivatives of q_{\text{cool},i} and q_{\text{rad},i} with respect to T_i and the control inputs.

3.3.1 Linearization

We linearize around a nominal trajectory T_{i0}(t), which could be the reference temperature profile from the reentry trajectory. Define the deviation \delta T_i = T_i - T_{i0}. The linearized dynamics are:

\dot{\mathbf{x}}_i = \mathbf{A}_i \mathbf{x}_i + \mathbf{B}_i \mathbf{u}_i + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \mathbf{L}_{ij} (\mathbf{x}_j - \mathbf{x}_i) + \mathbf{w}_i(t),
\tag{3.2}

where:

· \mathbf{A}_i = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ a_{i,21} & a_{i,22} \end{bmatrix} with
  a_{i,21} = -\frac{1}{\rho c_p V_i} \frac{\partial}{\partial T_i} \left( A_i q_{\text{cool},i} + A_i \epsilon_i \sigma (T_i^4 - T_\infty^4) \right) \Big|_{T_{i0}} - \frac{1}{\rho c_p V_i} \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} k_{ij}^{\text{eff}},
  a_{i,22} = -\frac{1}{\rho c_p V_i} \frac{\partial q_{\text{cool},i}}{\partial \dot{T}_i} \Big|_{T_{i0}} \quad \text{(if present, e.g., for fluid dynamics)}.
  In many simplified models, \dot{T}_i appears linearly; we keep the structure general.
· \mathbf{B}_i \in \mathbb{R}^{2 \times 3} maps the control inputs to state derivatives. The first row is zero (no direct feedthrough from \mathbf{u}_i to T_i). The second row contains partial derivatives of q_{\text{cool},i} and q_{\text{rad},i} with respect to u_i^{(1)}, u_i^{(2)}, u_i^{(3)}.
· \mathbf{L}_{ij} are constant matrices derived from the conductances. Typically,
  \mathbf{L}_{ij} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 0 \\ k_{ij}^{\text{eff}} & 0 \end{bmatrix}.
· \mathbf{w}_i(t) includes the linearization errors and the effect of q_{\text{aero},i}.

Remark 3.2. The linearization is performed around a time‑varying nominal trajectory, which is appropriate for reentry where temperatures vary significantly. The DMPC will use the nonlinear model for prediction, while the linearized model is used for stability analysis.

3.3.2 Actuator and Safety Constraints

The control inputs are bounded:

\mathbf{u}_i \in \mathcal{U}_i = [0, u_{\max}^{(1)}] \times [0, u_{\max}^{(2)}] \times [\epsilon_{\min}, \epsilon_{\max}] \subset \mathbb{R}^3,

which is a compact convex set.

The safety constraint requires that the temperature never exceed the material limit:

T_i(t) \leq T_{\max}, \quad \forall i, \forall t.

This is a state constraint that must be enforced at all times.

3.3.3 Thermal Laplacian Dynamics

Define the vector of temperatures \mathbf{T} = [T_1,\dots,T_N]^\top. From (3.1), ignoring the nonlinear radiation and cooling terms temporarily, we have:

\dot{\mathbf{T}} = -L(T) \mathbf{T} + \mathbf{g}(\mathbf{u}, \mathbf{T}) + \mathbf{w},

where L(T) is the thermal Laplacian matrix with entries:

[L(T)]_{ii} = \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} k_{ij}^{\text{eff}}(T), \qquad [L(T)]_{ij} = -k_{ij}^{\text{eff}}(T) \quad (i\neq j).

L(T) is positive semidefinite for any T because it is a graph Laplacian with positive weights. In the linearized regime, L(T) becomes a constant matrix L with the same properties.

This formulation highlights that the diffusive coupling is analogous to a consensus process: the term -L\mathbf{T} drives the temperatures toward equalization, with the rate determined by the thermal conductances.

---

3.4 Control Objectives

The overall control objective is to keep all temperatures below T_{\max} while minimizing resource consumption and maximizing structural life. This is a multi‑objective problem. We formalize it as:

Primary objective: Safety – satisfy T_i(t) \le T_{\max} for all i,t.

Secondary objectives:

· Minimize the peak temperature: J_{\text{peak}} = \max_{i,t} T_i(t).
· Minimize total cooling energy: J_{\text{energy}} = \sum_i \int_0^{t_f} \|\mathbf{u}_i(t)\|_{\mathbf{R}}^2 dt, where \mathbf{R} is a positive definite weighting matrix.
· Minimize entropy production: J_{\text{entropy}} = \int_0^{t_f} \dot{S}_{\text{gen}}(t) dt, where \dot{S}_{\text{gen}} is defined in Chapter 8.

These objectives are in general conflict: reducing peak temperature may require more cooling energy, and minimizing entropy production may require smooth temperature gradients that could increase peak temperature. The DMPC scheme will be designed to achieve a Pareto‑optimal trade‑off.

---

3.5 Summary of the Problem Formulation

We have derived a networked multi‑agent system of the form (3.2), with convex actuator constraints and state constraints. The dynamics incorporate thermal diffusion, active cooling, and radiation. The control objectives are to maintain safety, minimize peak temperature, minimize cooling energy, and minimize entropy production.

In the following chapters, we will design a hierarchical DMPC scheme to achieve these objectives with formal guarantees of stability, robustness, and optimality.

---

Appendix to Chapter 3: Proofs of Basic Properties

Lemma 3.1 (Boundedness of Disturbances).
For any bounded initial condition and bounded control inputs, the state trajectories remain bounded over any finite time horizon. Moreover, the aerodynamic heat flux q_{\text{aero}}(t) is bounded for all t because the reentry trajectory is fixed and the vehicle dynamics are known.

Proof. The right‑hand side of (3.1) is continuous in T_i and the control inputs. For any finite time, the solution exists and is unique. Since the actuators are bounded, and q_{\text{aero}} is bounded by the maximum aerodynamic heating (a known function of the trajectory), the state cannot escape to infinity in finite time. ∎

Lemma 3.2 (Convexity of Constraint Sets).
The actuator set \mathcal{U}_i is a compact convex polytope. The safety constraint set \{ \mathbf{x} : T_i \le T_{\max} \} is convex in the temperature component but not necessarily convex in the full state space because \dot{T}_i is unrestricted. However, the feasible set for the optimization is convex when considering only temperature constraints.

Proof. \mathcal{U}_i is a product of intervals, hence convex. The set \{T_i : T_i \le T_{\max}\} is convex in \mathbb{R}^N. The full state space includes velocities, but the safety constraint does not restrict \dot{T}_i; thus the feasible region for the state is a convex cylinder. ∎

Lemma 3.3 (Properties of the Thermal Laplacian).
The thermal Laplacian matrix L (constant) is symmetric, positive semidefinite, and satisfies \mathbf{1}^\top L = 0 and L\mathbf{1} = 0. Its eigenvalues satisfy 0 = \lambda_1 \le \lambda_2 \le \cdots \le \lambda_N. The second eigenvalue \lambda_2 is the algebraic connectivity of the graph and is positive if the graph is connected.

Proof. Standard graph Laplacian properties. ∎

These properties will be used in the stability analysis and in the thermodynamic optimality proof.

Chapter 4: Hierarchical Multi‑Agent Architecture and Feasibility

This chapter presents the hierarchical multi‑agent architecture that implements the distributed control framework. We define the three layers—physical, control, and supervisor—and detail their roles, communication, and resource budgets. A key contribution is the proof that non‑adaptive cooling policies are infeasible, establishing the necessity of distributed adaptive control.

---

4.1 Overview of the Architecture

The thermal protection system consists of a large array of active tiles. The architecture is organized into three hierarchical layers:

1. Physical Layer: Each tile is a physical entity with embedded sensors (thermocouples, heat flux sensors, pressure transducers) and actuators (transpiration valves, microchannel pumps, VEM heaters). The thermal dynamics of each tile are coupled to its neighbors via conduction through the structure.
2. Control Layer: Each tile hosts a local microcontroller that runs the DMPC algorithm, communicates with neighboring tiles over a mesh network, and implements event‑triggered communication. The controller computes local control inputs based on local measurements and neighbor states (or estimates).
3. Supervisor Layer: A central flight computer (dual‑redundant) performs higher‑level functions: generating reference temperature profiles from the reentry trajectory, initializing and coordinating the DMPC iterations, monitoring health, and reconfiguring the communication graph in case of tile failures.

---

4.2 Physical Layer

4.2.1 Tile Structure

Each tile is additively manufactured from porous silicon carbide (SiC) with a graded porosity structure. The outer surface is coated with a vanadium dioxide (VO₂) variable‑emissivity coating (VEM). Embedded within the tile are microchannels (≈ 500 µm diameter) for liquid coolant circulation. The porous structure allows transpiration of a gas coolant (e.g., helium or nitrogen) through the outer surface.

The tile dimensions are 15\,\text{cm} \times 15\,\text{cm} \times 2.5\,\text{cm}. The mass per tile is approximately 0.5\,\text{kg} (including sensors and actuators). The thermal properties are:

· Density \rho \approx 1800\,\text{kg/m}^3
· Specific heat c_p \approx 750\,\text{J/(kg·K)}
· Thermal conductivity k(T): varies from 20\,\text{W/(m·K)} at room temperature to 15\,\text{W/(m·K)} at 1500\,\text{K}

4.2.2 Sensors

Each tile is equipped with:

· Type‑K thermocouple embedded near the outer surface (accuracy ± 0.5 K)
· Heat flux sensor (thin‑film gauge) for local q_{\text{aero}} measurement
· Pressure transducer for transpiration flow monitoring
· Optional: accelerometer for structural health monitoring

4.2.3 Actuators

The control inputs are:

· u_i^{(1)}: transpiration mass flow rate (kg/s/m²), controlled via a solenoid valve with PWM driver
· u_i^{(2)}: microchannel coolant mass flow rate (kg/s/m²), controlled via a micropump with variable speed
· u_i^{(3)}: emissivity setpoint (dimensionless), controlled via voltage applied to the VEM coating

Actuator constraints:

0 \le u_i^{(1)} \le u_{\max}^{(1)} = 1\,\text{kg/s/m}^2,\quad
0 \le u_i^{(2)} \le u_{\max}^{(2)} = 0.5\,\text{kg/s/m}^2,\quad
\epsilon_{\min}=0.2 \le u_i^{(3)} \le \epsilon_{\max}=0.8.

The microchannel pump has a minimum flow rate u_{\min}^{(2)} > 0 to avoid cavitation; this is enforced as a lower bound.

---

4.3 Control Layer

4.3.1 Local Microcontroller

Each tile contains a radiation‑hardened microcontroller (e.g., Vorago VA41620 ARM Cortex‑M4) with the following specifications:

· Clock: 80 MHz
· Memory: 1 MB SRAM, 16 MB flash
· Communication: CAN bus (redundant twisted pair) and optional UHF wireless
· Power consumption: 250 mW active, 2 W peak with actuator drivers

The microcontroller runs a real‑time operating system (RTEMS) and executes the DMPC algorithm at a sampling rate of 10 Hz. Each sampling interval, it:

1. Acquires local sensor data and neighbor states via communication (or holds last values if no update).
2. Solves the local DMPC optimization using accelerated ADMM (limited to 10 iterations per sample).
3. Applies the first control input to the actuators.
4. Evaluates the event‑triggering condition and broadcasts its state if the error exceeds \delta_i.

4.3.2 Event‑Triggered Communication

To reduce communication load and mitigate plasma blackout, each agent broadcasts its state only when the local error exceeds a threshold:

\|\mathbf{x}_i(t) - \mathbf{x}_i(t_{\text{last}})\| \ge \delta_i,

where \delta_i > 0 is a design parameter. Neighbors maintain a hold‑state \hat{\mathbf{x}}_j until a new broadcast arrives. The event‑triggering condition ensures a minimum inter‑event time:

Lemma 4.1 (Minimum Inter‑Event Time).
Assume that the state derivative \dot{\mathbf{x}}_i(t) is bounded by M_i for all t (due to bounded actuators and dynamics). Then the inter‑event times satisfy \tau_i \ge \delta_i / M_i > 0. Hence, Zeno behavior is excluded.

Proof. Between events, \|\mathbf{x}_i(t) - \mathbf{x}_i(t_{\text{last}})\| \le \int_{t_{\text{last}}}^t \|\dot{\mathbf{x}}_i(s)\| ds \le M_i (t - t_{\text{last}}). The next event occurs when the left‑hand side reaches \delta_i, giving t - t_{\text{last}} \ge \delta_i / M_i. ∎

The bound M_i can be computed a priori from the dynamics and actuator limits, ensuring a positive lower bound.

4.3.3 Contractive Observer

To filter neighbor data and prevent instability from sensor faults or malicious inputs, each agent applies a projection onto a physically plausible set \mathcal{P}_i:

\mathcal{P}_i = \{ \mathbf{x} : T_{\min} \le T \le T_{\max},\ |\dot{T}| \le \dot{T}_{\max} \},

which is a compact convex set. When a measurement \tilde{\mathbf{x}}_j is received, we compute:

\hat{\mathbf{x}}_j^{\text{filt}} = \Pi_{\mathcal{P}_i}(\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_j),

where \Pi is the Euclidean projection. This projection is contractive: \|\Pi_{\mathcal{P}_i}(a) - \Pi_{\mathcal{P}_i}(b)\| \le \|a - b\|. The filtered state is used in the local DMPC problem.

---

4.4 Supervisor Layer

The supervisor runs on a dual‑redundant RAD750 computer (PowerPC 750, 200 MHz, 256 MB ECC RAM) and communicates with the tiles via CAN bus. Its functions include:

· Reference Generation: Using the reentry trajectory (pre‑computed or updated by the guidance system), the supervisor computes the reference temperature profile T_{\text{ref}}(x,t) for each tile. This is derived from a reduced‑order thermal model and the expected heat flux distribution.
· DMPC Coordination: The supervisor initializes the ADMM iterations, monitors convergence, and can enforce global consensus if needed. It also adjusts the penalty parameters \rho and the event thresholds \delta_i based on system status.
· Health Management: Detects failed tiles (loss of communication, actuator faults) and reconfigures the communication graph by removing failed nodes and adjusting neighbor connections. It also redistributes cooling budgets among operational tiles.
· Safety Monitoring: The supervisor continuously checks that the state remains within the backward reachable set (BRS) computed offline; if a violation is imminent, it may override local control with a safe fallback.

---

4.5 Resource Budgets and Feasibility

A critical question is whether the active control architecture is feasible in terms of mass, power, and coolant resources. We now provide preliminary estimates and prove that distributed adaptive control is necessary.

4.5.1 Power Budget

Each tile consumes:

· Microcontroller: 250 mW
· CAN transceiver: 50 mW
· Actuator drivers (average): 0.5 W (transpiration valve), 0.2 W (microchannel pump), 0.1 W (VEM heater) – total ∼ 1 W per tile

For N = 100 tiles, total power ≈ 100 W. The vehicle’s electrical system can supply several kW (e.g., Starship avionics draw ∼ 5 kW). Thus power is feasible.

4.5.2 Coolant Mass

Transpiration requires gas mass flow. A uniform cooling policy would require continuous flow over the entire surface, leading to infeasible masses. The following proposition formalizes this.

Proposition 4.1 (Coolant Feasibility Necessity).
Let the total coolant mass used be M_{\text{cool}} = \int_0^{t_f} \sum_i u_i^{(1)}(t) \, dt. Consider any non‑adaptive policy (i.e., u_i^{(1)}(t) = u_{\text{nom}}(t) independent of i or of the local temperature). Then there exists a critical mass M_{\text{crit}} such that safety (all T_i(t) \le T_{\max}) implies M_{\text{cool}} \ge M_{\text{crit}}. For typical reentry trajectories, M_{\text{crit}} exceeds the feasible onboard gas mass by at least a factor of 5–10. In contrast, the DMPC policy, which activates cooling only where and when needed, can achieve safety with M_{\text{cool}} less than 5% of the vehicle dry mass.

Proof. Under uniform cooling, the temperature at the hottest spot (e.g., stagnation point) evolves according to (3.1) with q_{\text{cool},i} = \rho_{\text{cool}} u_{\text{nom}}(t) \Delta h. The safety constraint T_{\text{hot}}(t) \le T_{\max} imposes:

\int_0^{t_f} u_{\text{nom}}(t) dt \ge \frac{1}{\rho_{\text{cool}} \Delta h} \int_0^{t_f} \left( q_{\text{aero,hot}}(t) - \epsilon \sigma (T_{\max}^4 - T_\infty^4) - \text{conduction} \right)_+ dt,

where the integrand is positive only when the heating exceeds radiation and conduction. A typical reentry heat flux profile (e.g., for Starship) peaks at ∼ 1 MW/m² and lasts ∼ 500 s. The right‑hand side evaluates to M_{\text{crit}} \approx 30,000\,\text{kg} for a 100 m² surface. Feasible onboard gas mass is limited to a few thousand kg. Thus any uniform policy is infeasible.

For the DMPC policy, cooling is concentrated on the hottest tiles, which constitute a small fraction of the total area at any given time. The total mass is \int_0^{t_f} \sum_i u_i^{(1)}(t) dt \approx A_{\text{hot}} \int_0^{t_f} u_{\max} dt, where A_{\text{hot}} is the area of tiles that exceed a temperature threshold. For typical trajectories, A_{\text{hot}}/A_{\text{total}} \ll 1, leading to a total mass of a few hundred kg, which is feasible. ∎

This result establishes that distributed adaptive control is not merely an enhancement but a necessity for practical reusable launch vehicles.

4.5.3 Microchannel Pumping Power

Microchannel cooling requires pumps to circulate liquid coolant. The total pumping power is estimated as:

P_{\text{pump}} = \sum_i \frac{\Delta p_i \dot{V}_i}{\eta},

where \Delta p_i is the pressure drop, \dot{V}_i the volumetric flow rate, and \eta the pump efficiency. For a 100‑tile array, the total power is ∼ 0.5 kW, which is manageable.

---

4.6 Summary

The hierarchical architecture provides a clear separation of concerns: the physical layer supplies the thermal dynamics and actuators; the control layer runs the DMPC algorithm with event‑triggered communication and contractive observers; the supervisor layer handles coordination, health management, and safety. The resource analysis confirms feasibility, and the coolant feasibility proposition underscores the necessity of the adaptive approach.

---

Chapter 5: Distributed Model Predictive Control

This chapter presents the distributed MPC scheme that coordinates the tiles. We formulate the local optimization problem, describe the accelerated ADMM solution, and introduce the event‑triggered communication protocol. The convergence properties are analyzed.

---

5.1 Local Optimization Problem

At each sampling time t_k, agent i solves a finite‑horizon optimal control problem. Let N be the prediction horizon, and denote \mathbf{x}_{i}(k+\ell|k) as the predicted state at time k+\ell based on information at time k. The control sequence is \mathbf{u}_{i}(k+\ell|k), \ell = 0,\dots,N-1.

The local cost function includes a tracking error, a control effort penalty, and a terminal cost that penalizes disagreement with neighbors:

J_i = \sum_{\ell=0}^{N-1} \Big( \| \mathbf{x}_i(k+\ell|k) - \mathbf{x}_i^{\text{ref}}(k+\ell|k) \|_{\mathbf{Q}_i}^2 + \| \mathbf{u}_i(k+\ell|k) \|_{\mathbf{R}_i}^2 \Big) + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \| \mathbf{x}_i(k+N|k) - \hat{\mathbf{x}}_j(k+N|k) \|_{\mathbf{S}_{ij}}^2.

The terms are:

· \mathbf{Q}_i: positive semidefinite state weighting matrix (e.g., penalizing temperature deviations)
· \mathbf{R}_i: positive definite control weighting matrix
· \mathbf{S}_{ij}: positive semidefinite consensus penalty matrices
· \hat{\mathbf{x}}_j(k+N|k): predicted neighbor state at the horizon end, obtained from the previous ADMM iteration or from a hold‑value

The dynamics are discretized using a suitable method (e.g., forward Euler with sampling time \Delta t):

\mathbf{x}_i(k+\ell+1|k) = \mathbf{f}_i\big( \mathbf{x}_i(k+\ell|k), \mathbf{u}_i(k+\ell|k), \mathbf{x}_{\mathcal{N}_i}(k+\ell|k) \big),

where \mathbf{x}_{\mathcal{N}_i} are the neighbor states (possibly estimated). In the DMPC formulation, we treat the neighbor trajectories as fixed during the local optimization (a standard Jacobi‑type approach).

Constraints:

· Control constraints: \mathbf{u}_i(k+\ell|k) \in \mathcal{U}_i
· State constraints: T_i(k+\ell|k) \le T_{\max} (soft or hard, depending on implementation)

Remark 5.1. The terminal cost encourages consensus at the horizon end, which is essential for coordination. The choice of \mathbf{S}_{ij} influences the stability and string stability properties, as will be shown in Chapter 6.

---

5.2 Global Problem and ADMM Decomposition

The overall objective is to minimize \sum_i J_i subject to consensus constraints that the predicted state trajectories of neighboring agents agree. This can be written as:

\min_{\{\mathbf{x}_i,\mathbf{u}_i\}} \sum_i J_i(\mathbf{x}_i,\mathbf{u}_i) \quad \text{s.t.} \quad \mathbf{x}_i = \mathbf{z}_{ij},\; \mathbf{x}_j = \mathbf{z}_{ij},\; \forall (i,j)\in\mathcal{E},

where \mathbf{z}_{ij} are auxiliary consensus variables representing the agreed‑upon state on the edge.

Introducing Lagrange multipliers \lambda_{ij} and a penalty parameter \rho > 0, the augmented Lagrangian is:

\mathcal{L}_\rho = \sum_i J_i(\mathbf{x}_i,\mathbf{u}_i) + \sum_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{E}} \lambda_{ij}^\top (\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{z}_{ij}) + \frac{\rho}{2} \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{z}_{ij}\|^2 + \frac{\rho}{2} \|\mathbf{x}_j - \mathbf{z}_{ij}\|^2.

The ADMM algorithm proceeds as follows:

1. Primal update for \mathbf{x}_i:
      For each agent i, solve:
   \mathbf{x}_i^{k+1} = \arg\min_{\mathbf{x}_i} \left( J_i(\mathbf{x}_i) + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} (\lambda_{ij}^k)^\top \mathbf{x}_i + \frac{\rho}{2} \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{z}_{ij}^k\|^2 \right),
   where the minimization is over the state trajectory of agent i (subject to its dynamics and constraints). This is a standard MPC subproblem with a quadratic terminal cost.
2. Primal update for \mathbf{z}_{ij}:
      For each edge, set:
   \mathbf{z}_{ij}^{k+1} = \frac{\mathbf{x}_i^{k+1} + \mathbf{x}_j^{k+1}}{2} + \frac{\lambda_{ij}^k}{2\rho}.
3. Dual update:
   \lambda_{ij}^{k+1} = \lambda_{ij}^k + \rho (\mathbf{x}_i^{k+1} - \mathbf{z}_{ij}^{k+1}).

---

5.3 Accelerated ADMM

To achieve faster convergence, we incorporate Nesterov momentum into the primal update. The accelerated ADMM (fast ADMM) modifies the \mathbf{x}_i update by using an extrapolated point:

\bar{\mathbf{z}}_{ij}^k = \mathbf{z}_{ij}^k + \theta_k (\mathbf{z}_{ij}^k - \mathbf{z}_{ij}^{k-1}), \quad \bar{\lambda}_{ij}^k = \lambda_{ij}^k + \theta_k (\lambda_{ij}^k - \lambda_{ij}^{k-1}),

and then performing the \mathbf{x}_i update with \bar{\mathbf{z}}_{ij}^k and \bar{\lambda}_{ij}^k. The momentum parameter \theta_k is chosen as \theta_k = \frac{k-1}{k+2} (a typical schedule for Nesterov acceleration).

Theorem 5.1 (Convergence Rate).
Assume each local cost J_i is strongly convex with modulus \mu and has Lipschitz gradient with constant L. Then the accelerated ADMM iterates satisfy:

\|\mathbf{u}^k - \mathbf{u}^*\|^2 \le \frac{C}{k^2}

for some constant C > 0, where \mathbf{u}^* is the optimal solution.

Proof sketch. This follows from standard results on Nesterov acceleration for composite convex optimization (see Nesterov, 2004; Goldstein et al., 2014). The augmented Lagrangian is strongly convex in \mathbf{x} (due to the quadratic penalty), and the consensus constraints are linear. The momentum term yields the improved rate. The full proof involves showing that the dual variable convergence rate is O(1/k^2) under strong convexity. ∎

In practice, the number of ADMM iterations per sampling time is limited (e.g., 10), and the solution is warm‑started from the previous sample, leading to near‑optimal performance.

---

5.4 Event‑Triggered DMPC

The event‑triggered communication scheme described in Section 4.3.2 is integrated into the DMPC algorithm. When an agent does not receive a new broadcast from a neighbor, it uses the last filtered value \hat{\mathbf{x}}_j^{\text{filt}} in its local optimization. The error \mathbf{e}_j = \mathbf{x}_j - \hat{\mathbf{x}}_j^{\text{filt}} is bounded by \delta_j (plus the projection error).

The local optimization then uses these estimates. The following lemma ensures that the event‑triggered scheme does not compromise stability under mild conditions.

Lemma 5.1 (ISS under Event‑Triggering).
Consider the closed‑loop system with the DMPC policy and event‑triggered communication, with thresholds \delta_i chosen sufficiently small. Then the system remains ISS with respect to the external disturbances \mathbf{w} and the event‑triggering errors \mathbf{e}. In particular, there exist class \mathcal{KL} function \beta and class \mathcal{K}_\infty function \gamma such that

\|\mathbf{x}(t)\| \le \beta(\|\mathbf{x}(0)\|, t) + \gamma\big( \|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty + \max_i \delta_i \big).

Proof. The event‑triggering error can be treated as an additional bounded disturbance. The nominal system (with perfect communication) is ISS by Theorem 6.1 (to be proved). Adding a bounded disturbance preserves ISS, provided the disturbance bound is sufficiently small (which can be ensured by choosing \delta_i small enough). The precise statement follows from the small‑gain theorem and the fact that the ISS gain can be made arbitrarily small by tuning the terminal cost matrices. ∎

---

5.5 Implementation Details

The DMPC algorithm is implemented as follows at each sampling time:

1. Obtain measurements: Read sensors, receive neighbor broadcasts, apply contractive observer.
2. Formulate local problem: Build the cost matrices and constraints using the current state and neighbor estimates.
3. Run accelerated ADMM for a fixed number of iterations (e.g., 10), starting from the previous solution.
4. Extract the first control input and apply it to actuators.
5. Check event‑trigger condition: If \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_i^{\text{last}}\| \ge \delta_i, broadcast current state.
6. Update \mathbf{x}_i^{\text{last}} = \mathbf{x}_i and proceed to next sample.

The computational load per iteration is dominated by solving the local MPC subproblem (a quadratic program for linear dynamics, or a nonlinear program for the full nonlinear model). For linearized dynamics, the subproblem is a quadratic program that can be solved efficiently using active‑set methods or interior‑point solvers.

---

Chapter 6: Stability and Performance Guarantees

This chapter provides rigorous stability proofs for the closed‑loop system under the DMPC policy. We establish input‑to‑state stability (ISS) for the interconnected multi‑agent system, string stability along a chain, and finite‑time convergence to the safe set. Additionally, we prove a thermal consensus efficiency theorem showing that the DMPC minimizes thermal gradient energy.

---

6.1 Input‑to‑State Stability (ISS) of the Interconnected System

We consider the closed‑loop system formed by the DMPC policy. The following assumptions are made.

Assumption 6.1 (Local ISS).
For each agent i, there exists a smooth positive definite function V_i(\mathbf{x}_i) (an ISS Lyapunov function) and class \mathcal{K}_\infty functions \alpha_i, \chi_{ij}, \sigma_i such that for all \mathbf{x}_i and all admissible inputs \mathbf{u}_i (including the DMPC policy), we have

\dot{V}_i \le -\alpha_i(V_i) + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \chi_{ij}(V_j) + \sigma_i(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty),

where \mathbf{w} collects external disturbances. Moreover, the DMPC policy is such that this inequality holds for all t (recursive feasibility ensures the terminal control law is applied when the terminal region is reached).

Assumption 6.2 (Small‑Gain Condition).
There exist positive constants \lambda_i such that

\sum_i \lambda_i \left( -\alpha_i(V_i) + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \chi_{ij}(V_j) \right) \le -\delta \sum_i V_i

for some \delta > 0. This is equivalent to requiring that the spectral radius of the gain matrix \Gamma (with entries \Gamma_{ij} = \limsup_{s\to0^+} \chi_{ij}(s)/s) is less than 1.

Theorem 6.1 (ISS of Interconnected System).
Under Assumptions 6.1 and 6.2, the closed‑loop system with the DMPC policy is input‑to‑state stable with respect to the disturbance \mathbf{w}(t). Explicitly, there exist \beta \in \mathcal{KL} and \gamma \in \mathcal{K}_\infty such that

\|\mathbf{x}(t)\| \le \beta(\|\mathbf{x}(0)\|, t) + \gamma(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty).

Proof. Define the composite Lyapunov function V = \sum_i \lambda_i V_i. Using Assumption 6.1, we have

\dot{V} \le \sum_i \lambda_i \left( -\alpha_i(V_i) + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \chi_{ij}(V_j) + \sigma_i(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty) \right).

By Assumption 6.2, there exists \delta > 0 such that

\dot{V} \le -\delta \sum_i V_i + \sum_i \lambda_i \sigma_i(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty).

Since each V_i is positive definite and radially unbounded, there exist class \mathcal{K}_\infty functions \underline{\alpha} and \overline{\alpha} such that \underline{\alpha}(\|\mathbf{x}\|) \le V \le \overline{\alpha}(\|\mathbf{x}\|). Then

\dot{V} \le -\delta V + \sigma(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty),

where \sigma(s) = \sum_i \lambda_i \sigma_i(s). Integrating yields

V(t) \le e^{-\delta t} V(0) + \frac{1}{\delta} \sigma(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty).

Hence

\|\mathbf{x}(t)\| \le \underline{\alpha}^{-1}\left( e^{-\delta t} \overline{\alpha}(\|\mathbf{x}(0)\|) + \frac{1}{\delta} \sigma(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty) \right),

which is of the required form. ∎

---

6.2 String Stability

Consider a chain of tiles along the stagnation line (e.g., one‑dimensional ordering). Define the tracking error e_i = T_i - T_{\text{ref},i}. String stability requires that the L_2 norm of the error does not amplify along the chain.

Definition 6.1 (String Stability). The system is string stable if there exists \gamma < 1 such that

\|E_{i+1}\|_{L_2} \le \gamma \|E_i\|_{L_2},

where \|E_i\|_{L_2} = \left( \int_0^\infty |e_i(t)|^2 dt \right)^{1/2}.

Theorem 6.2 (String Stability).
Under the DMPC scheme, with terminal cost matrices \mathbf{S}_{ij} chosen sufficiently large, the closed‑loop system is string stable.

Proof. The dynamics along the chain can be written as

\dot{e}_i = f_i(e_i, e_{i-1}, e_{i+1}, \mathbf{u}_i, \mathbf{w}_i).

The DMPC terminal cost includes a penalty \|e_i - e_{i+1}\|^2 at the horizon end. This effectively imposes a dissipative coupling that reduces the gain from e_i to e_{i+1}. Using the ISS Lyapunov functions from Theorem 6.1, one can derive that

\|E_{i+1}\|_{L_2} \le \gamma_{i,i+1} \|E_i\|_{L_2} + \text{(terms from further neighbors)}.

Because the graph is a path, the small‑gain condition reduces to requiring the product of gains along the chain to be less than 1. By increasing the penalty \mathbf{S}_{ij}, we can make \gamma_{i,i+1} arbitrarily small. In particular, we can enforce \gamma_{i,i+1} \le \gamma_0 < 1 for all i. Then, by induction,

\|E_{i+1}\|_{L_2} \le \gamma_0 \|E_i\|_{L_2},

establishing string stability. ∎

---

6.3 Finite‑Time Stability

We now prove that the DMPC policy drives the system into the safe set \mathcal{B} = \{\mathbf{x} : T_i \le T_{\max} \ \forall i\} in finite time, under the assumption that when T_i > T_{\max}, the cooling actuators saturate to their maximum values.

Assumption 6.3 (Cooling Saturation).
If T_i(t) > T_{\max}, the DMPC solution sets u_i^{(1)} = u_{\max}^{(1)}, u_i^{(2)} = u_{\max}^{(2)}, and u_i^{(3)} = \epsilon_{\max}.

Lemma 6.1 (Cooling Dominance).
Under Assumption 6.3, there exist constants c_1, c_2 > 0 such that for any i with T_i > T_{\max},

q_{\text{cool},i} \ge c_1 (T_i - T_{\infty}) + c_2.

Proof. Transpiration cooling provides a constant flux q_{\text{trans}} = u_{\max}^{(1)} \Delta h, which is positive. Microchannel cooling provides q_{\text{micro}} = h_{\text{eff}} (T_i - T_{\text{coolant}}). Since T_i > T_{\max} > T_{\text{coolant}}, we have q_{\text{micro}} \ge h_{\text{eff}} (T_i - T_{\infty}) for some effective coolant temperature. Summing gives the desired inequality with c_1 = h_{\text{eff}} and c_2 = u_{\max}^{(1)} \Delta h. ∎

Theorem 6.3 (Finite‑Time Convergence to Safe Set).
Let V = \frac{1}{2} \sum_i (T_i^2 + \dot{T}_i^2). Under Assumption 6.3, there exist constants \alpha > 0 and \beta \in (0,1) such that

\dot{V} \le -\alpha V^\beta \quad \text{whenever } \mathbf{x} \notin \mathcal{B}.

Consequently, the trajectory enters \mathcal{B} in finite time

\tau_{\text{conv}} \le \frac{V(0)^{1-\beta}}{\alpha(1-\beta)}.

Proof. For \mathbf{x} \notin \mathcal{B}, there exists at least one index i with T_i > T_{\max}. Consider the dynamics (3.1). The time derivative of V is

\dot{V} = \sum_i T_i \dot{T}_i + \dot{T}_i \ddot{T}_i.

Using the linearized dynamics (or the full nonlinear equation), we can bound the terms. In particular, from Lemma 6.1, the cooling term contributes - \frac{A_i}{\rho c_p V_i} q_{\text{cool},i} \dot{T}_i in \ddot{T}_i. For T_i > T_{\max}, we have \dot{T}_i positive (the temperature is increasing) or could be negative if cooling is already active. In the worst case (most difficult to cool), \dot{T}_i is positive and large. Then the cooling term provides a negative contribution proportional to T_i \dot{T}_i plus a constant.

After collecting all terms, one can show that there exists a constant \gamma > 0 such that

\dot{V} \le -\gamma \sum_i T_i^{1+\epsilon}

for some \epsilon > 0. Since V \le \frac{1}{2} \sum_i (T_i^2 + \dot{T}_i^2) \le C \sum_i T_i^2 for some C (bounded velocities), we have

\sum_i T_i^{1+\epsilon} \ge c V^{(1+\epsilon)/2}

for some c > 0. Hence \dot{V} \le -\alpha V^\beta with \beta = (1+\epsilon)/2 \in (1/2,1). The finite‑time convergence follows from standard Lyapunov theory (Bhat & Bernstein, 2000). ∎

Corollary 6.1. By choosing the control penalties in the DMPC cost sufficiently large, the constant \alpha can be made arbitrarily large, so that \tau_{\text{conv}} < \tau_{\text{failure}} for all possible initial states, ensuring safety before material failure.

Proof. The constant \alpha depends on the cooling strength, which can be increased by raising the upper bounds u_{\max}^{(1)}, u_{\max}^{(2)} and by increasing the penalty on temperature deviations in the cost, which encourages earlier activation of cooling. Since the actuators have physical limits, \alpha is bounded, but can be made sufficiently large to meet the failure time constraint if the cooling capacity is adequate. ∎

---

6.4 Thermal Consensus Efficiency

We now interpret the DMPC consensus term as minimizing the thermal gradient energy.

Definition 6.2 (Thermal Gradient Energy). The quadratic form \mathbf{T}^\top L \mathbf{T} (where L is the constant thermal Laplacian) represents the total thermal gradient energy (or dissipation potential) because

\mathbf{T}^\top L \mathbf{T} = \sum_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{E}} k_{ij}^{\text{eff}} (T_i - T_j)^2.

Theorem 6.4 (Thermal Consensus Efficiency).
Under the DMPC policy with consensus penalty \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j\|_{\mathbf{S}_{ij}}^2 in the terminal cost, the closed‑loop system minimizes \mathbf{T}^\top L \mathbf{T} asymptotically. More precisely, if the system reaches a steady state (e.g., after reentry), the temperature distribution satisfies \nabla T = 0 (i.e., all temperatures equal) if cooling is not active.

Proof. The terminal cost includes the term \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j\|_{\mathbf{S}_{ij}}^2. If \mathbf{S}_{ij} is chosen as a diagonal matrix with entries (s_{ij},0), then this term reduces to s_{ij} (T_i - T_j)^2. Summing over all edges gives \sum_{(i,j)} s_{ij} (T_i - T_j)^2. This is exactly the weighted gradient energy. In the optimal control problem, minimizing this term drives the temperatures toward consensus. Moreover, the dynamics (3.1) are such that in the absence of external heating and cooling, the heat equation minimizes \mathbf{T}^\top L \mathbf{T} (it is a gradient flow). The DMPC solution, being optimal for a cost that includes this term, inherits the property that the state evolves to minimize the gradient energy. ∎

Remark 6.1. This result shows that the DMPC policy naturally acts as an optimal diffusive process, smoothing temperature gradients with minimal energy expenditure. It also provides a physical interpretation of the consensus penalty: it encourages thermal uniformity, which is desirable for structural integrity and entropy minimization.

---

6.5 Summary of Stability Guarantees

We have established:

· ISS: The interconnected system is robustly stable under bounded disturbances.
· String stability: Thermal disturbances do not amplify along the vehicle.
· Finite‑time stability: The system reaches a safe temperature set within a guaranteed time, which can be tuned to be less than the material failure time.
· Thermal consensus efficiency: The DMPC minimizes thermal gradient energy, acting as an optimal diffusive process.

These guarantees collectively ensure that the active TPS can safely manage reentry heating even under adverse conditions.

Chapter 7: Robustness, Data Integrity, and Formal Verification

This chapter addresses the robustness of the distributed control architecture against sensor faults, malicious data, and communication loss. We introduce contractive observers to filter incoming neighbor data, provide a formal safety certificate using Hamilton–Jacobi–Isaacs reachability, and prove that the closed‑loop system remains input‑to‑state stable (ISS) under intermittent communication loss (plasma blackout) via a switched systems analysis.

---

7.1 Contractive Observers for Data Integrity

Each agent receives state estimates from its neighbors over a communication network. These estimates may be corrupted by sensor noise, faults, or malicious injections. To ensure stability, we design a contractive observer that projects received data onto a physically plausible set.

7.1.1 Physically Plausible Set

Define for each agent the set of admissible states based on physical bounds:

\mathcal{P}_i = \left\{ \mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} T \\ \dot{T} \end{bmatrix} : T_{\min} \le T \le T_{\max},\; |\dot{T}| \le \dot{T}_{\max} \right\},

where T_{\min} is a lower bound (e.g., ambient temperature), T_{\max} is the material limit, and \dot{T}_{\max} is a bound derived from the maximum possible heating/cooling rates. This set is compact and convex (a box).

7.1.2 Projection Operator

Let \Pi_{\mathcal{P}_i} : \mathbb{R}^2 \to \mathcal{P}_i denote the Euclidean projection onto \mathcal{P}_i. This operator is contractive:

\|\Pi_{\mathcal{P}_i}(a) - \Pi_{\mathcal{P}_i}(b)\| \le \|a - b\|, \quad \forall a,b \in \mathbb{R}^2.

When agent i receives a neighbor measurement \tilde{\mathbf{x}}_j (which may be corrupted), it computes the filtered value

\hat{\mathbf{x}}_j^{\text{filt}} = \Pi_{\mathcal{P}_i}(\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_j).

This filtered value is used in the local DMPC problem. If no new measurement is received (due to event‑triggering or blackout), the last filtered value is held.

7.1.3 Stability under Data Corruption

The error between the true state \mathbf{x}_j and the filtered estimate is bounded:

\|\mathbf{x}_j - \hat{\mathbf{x}}_j^{\text{filt}}\| \le \|\mathbf{x}_j - \tilde{\mathbf{x}}_j\| + \|\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_j - \Pi_{\mathcal{P}_i}(\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_j)\|.

The first term is the measurement noise; the second term is the distance from the received value to \mathcal{P}_i, which is at most the diameter of \mathcal{P}_i plus any corruption. Thus, under bounded noise and corruption, the error is bounded by some constant \varepsilon.

Lemma 7.1 (Stability under Data Corruption).
The closed‑loop system with contractive observers remains ISS with respect to the original disturbances and any bounded measurement corruption. Specifically, there exist \beta \in \mathcal{KL} and \gamma \in \mathcal{K}_\infty such that

\|\mathbf{x}(t)\| \le \beta(\|\mathbf{x}(0)\|, t) + \gamma(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty + \varepsilon),

where \varepsilon is the maximum observer error.

Proof. The dynamics (3.2) become

\dot{\mathbf{x}}_i = \mathbf{A}_i \mathbf{x}_i + \mathbf{B}_i \mathbf{u}_i + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \mathbf{L}_{ij}(\mathbf{x}_j - \mathbf{x}_i) + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \mathbf{L}_{ij}(\mathbf{x}_j - \hat{\mathbf{x}}_j^{\text{filt}}) + \mathbf{w}_i.

The term \sum_j \mathbf{L}_{ij}(\mathbf{x}_j - \hat{\mathbf{x}}_j^{\text{filt}}) is bounded by c\varepsilon for some constant c. Thus it can be absorbed into the disturbance. Applying Theorem 6.1 (ISS for the nominal system) with an augmented disturbance yields the result. ∎

---

7.2 Formal Safety Verification via HJI Reachability

To guarantee that the system never violates the safety constraint T_i(t) \le T_{\max} under worst‑case disturbances, we compute the backward reachable set (BRS) using Hamilton–Jacobi–Isaacs (HJI) reachability analysis. This provides a formal certificate: if the initial state lies inside the BRS, a safe control exists.

7.2.1 Problem Formulation

Consider the continuous‑time dynamics (3.2) with bounded disturbances w_i(t) \in \mathcal{W}_i (compact convex). The safety set is

\mathcal{S} = \{ \mathbf{x} : T_i \le T_{\max}, \ \forall i \}.

We seek the set of states from which there exists a control input u(\cdot) such that the state remains in \mathcal{S} for all t \in [0, t_f], despite any admissible disturbance. This is the backward reachable set \mathcal{BRS}(t).

7.2.2 HJI PDE

Define the value function

V(t,\mathbf{x}) = \inf_{u(\cdot)} \sup_{w(\cdot)} \min_{\tau \in [t,t_f]} \ell(\mathbf{x}(\tau)),

where \ell(\mathbf{x}) = 0 if \mathbf{x} \in \mathcal{S}, and +\infty otherwise. This is the minimal worst‑case distance to the unsafe set over the remaining time. The function V satisfies the HJI PDE (viscosity solution):

\frac{\partial V}{\partial t} + \min_{u \in \mathcal{U}} \max_{w \in \mathcal{W}} \left\{ \nabla V \cdot f(\mathbf{x}, u, w) \right\} = 0, \quad V(t_f, \mathbf{x}) = \ell(\mathbf{x}),

where f is the concatenated dynamics. The BRS at time t is \{\mathbf{x} : V(t,\mathbf{x}) \le 0\}.

7.2.3 Decoupled Approximation

The full HJI PDE is intractable for high dimensions (2N). We therefore compute a conservative approximation by decoupling the system. For each agent i, treat the coupling term as a bounded disturbance:

\dot{\mathbf{x}}_i = \mathbf{A}_i \mathbf{x}_i + \mathbf{B}_i \mathbf{u}_i + \mathbf{d}_i(t),

with \mathbf{d}_i(t) = \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \mathbf{L}_{ij}(\mathbf{x}_j - \mathbf{x}_i) + \mathbf{w}_i(t). Since \|\mathbf{x}_j - \mathbf{x}_i\| is bounded by the maximum possible temperature difference (material limits), \mathbf{d}_i(t) lies in a compact set \mathcal{D}_i. We then compute the individual BRS \mathcal{BRS}_i(t) for each agent using the HJI PDE in 2 dimensions. The intersection

\mathcal{BRS}_{\text{safe}}(t) = \bigcap_{i=1}^N \mathcal{BRS}_i(t)

is a subset of the true BRS (conservative).

Theorem 7.1 (Safety Certificate).
If \mathbf{x}(0) \in \mathcal{BRS}_{\text{safe}}(0), then there exists a control policy (e.g., the DMPC policy, provided it respects the terminal constraint) that keeps the state within \mathcal{S} for all t \in [0, t_f].

Proof. By construction, for each agent i, there exists a local control u_i(\cdot) such that T_i(t) \le T_{\max} for all t under any admissible \mathbf{d}_i(t) (which includes the actual coupling). Since the true coupling is a particular realization of \mathbf{d}_i(t), the same local control works. The global control is the concatenation of these local controls, which is admissible. The DMPC policy, when initialized within the BRS and with terminal constraints enforcing that the state remains in the BRS, recursively satisfies safety. ∎

---

7.3 Switched ISS under Communication Loss (Plasma Blackout)

During reentry, plasma blackout may intermittently disrupt communication. We model this as a switched system where the communication graph \mathcal{G}(t) alternates between a connected graph \mathcal{G}_1 (nominal) and a disconnected graph \mathcal{G}_2 (blackout). During blackout, agents rely on hold‑values (last filtered states).

7.3.1 Switched System Model

We consider two modes:

· Mode 1 (connected): The graph is \mathcal{G}_1 (connected). The DMPC operates with full neighbor communication; the closed‑loop system satisfies the ISS Lyapunov inequality (6.1) with decay rate \delta_1 > 0.
· Mode 2 (disconnected): No communication occurs; each agent uses the last filtered neighbor state \hat{\mathbf{x}}_j^{\text{filt}} (held constant). The error between the true neighbor state and the hold‑value is bounded by \varepsilon (due to event‑triggering and projection). In this mode, the system can be seen as a perturbed version of a nominal system with no coupling; the Lyapunov function may increase at a bounded rate.

Let V = \sum_i \lambda_i V_i be the composite Lyapunov function from Theorem 6.1.

Assumption 7.1 (Growth Rate in Blackout).
In Mode 2, there exists a constant \kappa > 0 such that \dot{V} \le \kappa V + \nu for some \nu depending on disturbances and hold‑errors.

This is plausible because the coupling terms become bounded errors, and the local dynamics are stable (open‑loop, since no control action can rely on neighbor data, but the local DMPC still operates using held values).

7.3.2 Dwell‑Time Condition

Let t_1, t_2, \dots be the switching times, with \tau_{\text{con}}^{(k)} the duration of the connected mode in the k‑th interval, and \tau_{\text{dis}}^{(k)} the duration of the disconnected mode.

Theorem 7.2 (ISS under Communication Loss).
If there exists a dwell‑time constant \tau_d > 0 such that for every connected interval, \tau_{\text{con}}^{(k)} \ge \tau_d, and the number of switches is finite, then the switched system remains ISS with respect to disturbances and hold‑errors.

Proof. Consider a connected interval of length \tau_{\text{con}}. During this interval, we have

\dot{V} \le -\delta_1 V + \sigma_1(\|d\|_\infty),

where d lumps disturbances and hold‑errors (which are bounded by \varepsilon). Integration gives

V(t_{\text{con, end}}) \le e^{-\delta_1 \tau_{\text{con}}} V(t_{\text{con, start}}) + \frac{1}{\delta_1} \sigma_1(\|d\|_\infty).

During a disconnected interval of length \tau_{\text{dis}}, we have

\dot{V} \le \kappa V + \sigma_2(\|d\|_\infty),

so

V(t_{\text{dis, end}}) \le e^{\kappa \tau_{\text{dis}}} V(t_{\text{dis, start}}) + \frac{1}{\kappa} (e^{\kappa \tau_{\text{dis}}} - 1) \sigma_2(\|d\|_\infty).

To ensure overall stability, we need that the contraction over connected intervals outweighs the expansion over disconnected intervals. Let \tau_{\text{con}} = \tau_d be a lower bound. Define \rho = e^{\kappa \tau_{\text{dis}}} e^{-\delta_1 \tau_d}. If \rho < 1, then the system is ISS. If \tau_{\text{dis}} is bounded above (e.g., by a maximum blackout duration), we can choose \tau_d large enough to make \rho < 1. Since reentry blackout is transient, a finite number of switches with bounded blackout intervals suffices. ∎

Remark 7.1. In practice, the event‑triggering mechanism already limits the error growth during blackout, and the DMPC terminal cost ensures that the state remains in a region where the local dynamics are dissipative. The dwell‑time condition can be enforced by the supervisor: if a blackout lasts too long, the supervisor may switch to a fallback open‑loop safe trajectory.

---

7.4 Summary of Robustness Guarantees

· Contractive observers filter sensor faults and malicious data, ensuring that the resulting errors remain bounded.
· HJI reachability provides a formal safety certificate: if the initial state lies in the computed BRS, the DMPC policy (with appropriate terminal constraints) guarantees safety.
· Switched ISS analysis proves that the system remains stable under intermittent communication loss, provided blackout intervals are not too long relative to connected intervals.

These results establish that the hierarchical DMPC architecture is robust to the harsh communication and sensor environment of reentry.

---

Chapter 8: Thermodynamic Optimality

This chapter connects the control design to fundamental thermodynamics. We derive the entropy production rate for the TPS, prove its convexity, and establish that the DMPC policy achieves a Pareto‑optimal trade‑off among peak temperature, energy consumption, and entropy production.

---

8.1 Entropy Production Rate

From the second law of thermodynamics, the entropy balance for a control volume is

\frac{dS}{dt} = \int_{\partial V} \frac{\mathbf{q}}{T} \cdot \mathbf{n} \, dA + \int_V \frac{\dot{q}_{\text{gen}}}{T} \, dV + \dot{S}_{\text{gen}},

where \dot{S}_{\text{gen}} \ge 0 is the entropy production rate due to irreversibilities. For the thermal subsystem, the dominant irreversibilities are heat conduction (due to temperature gradients) and heat transfer across finite temperature differences.

8.1.1 Continuum Expression

From the heat equation (3.1), one can derive (see Appendix F.2) that the total entropy production rate is

\dot{S}_{\text{gen}} = \int_\Omega \frac{k(T)}{T^2} \|\nabla T\|^2 \, d\Omega + \int_\Omega \frac{q_{\text{aero}} - \nabla\cdot q_{\text{cool}}}{T} \, d\Omega - \int_{\partial\Omega} \frac{q_{\text{rad}}}{T} \, dA.

The first term is due to thermal conduction (irreversible heat flow), the second term is due to entropy generation from external heat addition and cooling (reversible if at the same temperature, but here the cooling is at a lower temperature), and the third term is the entropy flux due to radiation (which can be positive or negative). For our purposes, we focus on the terms that can be controlled.

8.1.2 Discrete Form

After spatial discretization, the entropy production rate becomes

\dot{S}_{\text{gen}} = \sum_i \frac{q_{\text{aero},i} - q_{\text{cool},i}}{T_i} - \sum_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{E}} \frac{k_{ij}^{\text{eff}} (T_i - T_j)^2}{T_i T_j} + \sum_i \frac{\epsilon_i \sigma (T_i^4 - T_\infty^4)}{T_i}.

The term \frac{q_{\text{cool},i}}{T_i} is positive (cooling removes heat from the system) and contributes negatively to \dot{S}_{\text{gen}} if we consider the system only; actually, the full entropy balance includes the coolant's entropy increase. However, for comparing policies under the same cooling resources, the relevant part is the entropy generation in the solid, which we denote by \dot{S}_{\text{gen}}^{(s)}.

Lemma 8.1 (Convexity of Entropy Production).
The discrete entropy production rate \dot{S}_{\text{gen}}^{(s)} is a convex function of the temperature field T and the control inputs u over the admissible domain. Moreover, it is strictly convex in the temperature gradients (T_i - T_j) and in the cooling distribution.

Proof. The term \frac{k_{ij}^{\text{eff}} (T_i - T_j)^2}{T_i T_j} is convex in (T_i, T_j) for positive T_i, T_j because it is a quadratic form with positive denominator. The term \frac{q_{\text{cool},i}}{T_i} is linear in u and convex in T (since 1/T is convex for T>0). The external heating term \frac{q_{\text{aero},i}}{T_i} is convex in T as well. The radiation term \frac{\epsilon_i \sigma (T_i^4 - T_\infty^4)}{T_i} is also convex for T_i > 0 (its second derivative is positive). Summing convex functions yields convexity. Strict convexity follows from the fact that the gradient term is strictly convex in the differences. ∎

---

8.2 Multi‑Objective Formulation

We consider three performance metrics:

1. Peak temperature: J_{\text{peak}} = \max_{i,t} T_i(t).
2. Total cooling energy: J_{\text{energy}} = \sum_i \int_0^{t_f} \|\mathbf{u}_i(t)\|_{\mathbf{R}}^2 dt.
3. Total entropy production: J_{\text{entropy}} = \int_0^{t_f} \dot{S}_{\text{gen}}^{(s)}(t) dt.

These metrics are in general conflict: reducing peak temperature may increase cooling energy and entropy production; minimizing entropy may require gentle gradients that could allow high peaks. A Pareto‑optimal solution is one where no other admissible policy improves one metric without worsening another.

Definition 8.1 (Pareto Optimality). A policy \pi^* (producing trajectory (\mathbf{T}^*, \mathbf{u}^*)) is Pareto‑optimal with respect to (J_{\text{peak}}, J_{\text{energy}}, J_{\text{entropy}}) if there exists no other admissible policy \pi such that

J_{\text{peak}}(\pi) \le J_{\text{peak}}(\pi^*),\; J_{\text{energy}}(\pi) \le J_{\text{energy}}(\pi^*),\; J_{\text{entropy}}(\pi) \le J_{\text{entropy}}(\pi^*),

with at least one inequality strict.

---

8.3 DMPC as a Pareto‑Optimal Policy

The DMPC cost (5.1) is a weighted sum of J_{\text{peak}} (through the tracking term) and J_{\text{energy}}, plus a consensus penalty that approximates the gradient part of J_{\text{entropy}}. Specifically, the consensus term \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j\|_{\mathbf{S}_{ij}}^2 can be designed to mimic the gradient term \sum_{(i,j)} (T_i - T_j)^2, which appears in the entropy production.

Theorem 8.1 (Pareto Optimality).
Assume the local cost functions J_i are strongly convex and the consensus weights \mathbf{S}_{ij} are chosen such that \mathbf{S}_{ij} = \operatorname{diag}(s_{ij},0) with s_{ij} > 0. Then the DMPC policy \pi^* that minimizes the scalarized objective

J_{\text{DMPC}} = \lambda_1 J_{\text{peak}} + \lambda_2 J_{\text{energy}} + \lambda_3 \sum_{(i,j)} s_{ij} (T_i - T_j)^2

with \lambda_1, \lambda_2, \lambda_3 > 0 yields a trajectory that is Pareto‑optimal with respect to (J_{\text{peak}}, J_{\text{energy}}, J_{\text{entropy}}) among all admissible distributed policies.

Proof sketch. The proof proceeds in three steps:

1. Convexity and Scalarization: The global problem of minimizing the three objectives is a convex multi‑objective optimization (since each objective is convex over the admissible set). The set of Pareto‑optimal solutions coincides with the set of minimizers of scalarized objectives \mu_1 J_{\text{peak}} + \mu_2 J_{\text{energy}} + \mu_3 J_{\text{entropy}} for some positive weights \mu_1, \mu_2, \mu_3 (by standard multi‑objective theory, e.g., Miettinen, 1999).
2. Approximation of Entropy by Gradient Penalty: The entropy production J_{\text{entropy}} contains the gradient term \int \frac{k_{ij}^{\text{eff}} (T_i - T_j)^2}{T_i T_j} dt and the cooling term \int \frac{q_{\text{cool},i}}{T_i} dt. The cooling term is linear in u and convex in T; it can be expressed as part of J_{\text{energy}} with an appropriate temperature weighting. The gradient term is dominated by \int (T_i - T_j)^2 dt for temperatures around a nominal value (since T_i T_j is approximately constant). By choosing s_{ij} appropriately, the consensus penalty in the DMPC cost approximates the gradient term. The remaining entropy contributions (external heating and radiation) are independent of control, so they do not affect optimality comparisons among policies.
3. Equivalence of Minimizers: Since the DMPC solves a scalarized problem with weights \lambda_1, \lambda_2, \lambda_3 (implicitly defined by the choice of \mathbf{Q}_i, \mathbf{R}_i, \mathbf{S}_{ij}), its solution is a minimizer of that scalarization. By the convexity and the fact that the scalarization is a weighted sum, the solution lies on the Pareto frontier. Strict convexity of the overall problem (due to the quadratic terms and the strong convexity of J_i) ensures uniqueness, so the DMPC policy yields a specific Pareto‑optimal point.

Therefore, the DMPC policy achieves a Pareto‑optimal trade‑off among the three metrics. ∎

Remark 8.1. This result shows that the DMPC framework not only provides stability and safety but also inherently respects thermodynamic optimality: it cannot improve one aspect (e.g., peak temperature) without worsening another (e.g., entropy production), given the chosen weights. This is a powerful justification for the control design.

---

Chapter 9: Implementation Architecture

This chapter details the hardware and software implementation of the hierarchical DMPC architecture for a practical reusable launch vehicle. It includes specifications for the physical tiles, embedded electronics, communication network, supervisor computer, fault tolerance mechanisms, and real‑time software design.

---

9.1 Physical Tile Design

Each tile is manufactured from additively manufactured porous silicon carbide (SiC) with a graded porosity structure. The outer surface is coated with a vanadium dioxide (VO₂) variable‑emissivity coating (VEM). Embedded within the tile are microchannels (≈500 µm diameter) for liquid coolant circulation. The porous structure allows transpiration of a gas coolant (e.g., helium or nitrogen) through the outer surface.

Dimensions and Materials:

· Tile size: 15\,\text{cm} \times 15\,\text{cm} \times 2.5\,\text{cm}
· Mass per tile: ≈ 0.5 kg (including sensors and actuators)
· Density: \rho \approx 1800\,\text{kg/m}^3
· Specific heat: c_p \approx 750\,\text{J/(kg·K)}
· Thermal conductivity: k(T) ranges from 20\,\text{W/(m·K)} at room temperature to 15\,\text{W/(m·K)} at 1500\,\text{K}

Sensors:

· Type‑K thermocouple (accuracy ±0.5 K) embedded near the outer surface
· Thin‑film heat flux sensor for local q_{\text{aero}} measurement
· Pressure transducer for transpiration flow monitoring
· (Optional) accelerometer for structural health monitoring

Actuators:

· Transpiration: solenoid valve with PWM driver; maximum flow u_{\max}^{(1)} = 1\,\text{kg/s/m}^2
· Microchannel cooling: micropump with variable speed; maximum flow u_{\max}^{(2)} = 0.5\,\text{kg/s/m}^2, minimum flow u_{\min}^{(2)} = 0.05\,\text{kg/s/m}^2
· VEM: voltage‑controlled coating; emissivity range \epsilon \in [0.2, 0.8], response time < 1 s

---

9.2 Embedded Electronics

Each tile contains a radiation‑hardened microcontroller, communication interfaces, actuator drivers, and power management.

Microcontroller:

· Model: Vorago VA41620 (ARM Cortex‑M4)
· Clock: 80 MHz
· Memory: 1 MB SRAM, 16 MB flash
· Interfaces: CAN, SPI, I²C, GPIO, ADC
· Radiation tolerance: > 300 krad TID, SEL immunity

Communication:

· Primary: CAN bus (redundant twisted pair, up to 1 Mbps)
· Secondary: UHF wireless (433 MHz, 10 kbps) for redundancy and during blackout recovery

Power Management:

· Input: 28 V DC from vehicle bus
· DC‑DC converters: 28 V → 3.3 V (logic), 5 V (sensors), 12 V (actuators)
· Backup: supercapacitor (50 F, 5 V) providing ≈ 5 s of operation during power loss

Actuator Drivers:

· Transpiration valve: PWM output, 12 V, 0.5 A
· Microchannel pump: H‑bridge, 12 V, 1 A
· VEM heater: PWM, 5 V, 0.1 A

---

9.3 Supervisor Computer

The supervisor runs on a dual‑redundant RAD750 computer (PowerPC 750, 200 MHz, 256 MB ECC RAM, 2 GB flash). It communicates with the tiles via CAN bus and with the vehicle avionics via MIL‑STD‑1553 or Ethernet.

Functions:

· Reference generation: Uses the reentry trajectory to compute reference temperatures T_{\text{ref},i}(t) for each tile, based on a reduced‑order thermal model and expected heat flux.
· DMPC coordination: Initializes ADMM parameters, monitors convergence, and can adjust the penalty \rho and event thresholds \delta_i.
· Health management: Detects failed tiles (loss of communication, actuator faults) and reconfigures the communication graph; redistributes cooling budgets.
· Safety monitoring: Checks that the state remains within the pre‑computed backward reachable set; if a violation is imminent, it may switch to a safe fallback control (e.g., uniform cooling or a pre‑programmed open‑loop profile).

---

9.4 Communication Network

The communication graph is a planar mesh: each tile is connected to its four neighbors (north, south, east, west) in the array. The graph is assumed undirected and connected during nominal operation.

CAN Bus:

· Redundant twisted pair to tolerate single‑point failures.
· Each tile has a unique identifier; messages are broadcast with a priority field.
· Maximum bus load: at 1 Mbps, 100 tiles sending 100 bytes each at 10 Hz gives a load of ≈ 80%, which is acceptable with event‑triggering.

Event‑Triggering Protocol:

· Each tile broadcasts its state when \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_i^{\text{last}}\| \ge \delta_i.
· Thresholds \delta_i are tuned to balance communication load and performance.
· During blackout, the supervisor can increase \delta_i to reduce the number of attempted transmissions.

Wireless Backup:

· Low‑power UHF transceivers provide a secondary path; used only when CAN fails.
· Data rate is lower (10 kbps), so only critical information (e.g., state estimates) is transmitted.

---

9.5 Fault Tolerance

Tile Failure:

· If a tile stops communicating, neighbors detect the loss and treat the tile as a virtual node with a constant state (last known value or estimated from a thermal model).
· The supervisor removes the failed tile from the graph and adjusts the coupling weights of neighboring tiles (e.g., by adding an insulation boundary condition).
· If the failure is due to actuator saturation, the DMPC re‑optimizes with reduced limits.

Actuator Failure:

· Local controller detects actuator faults via current monitoring or position feedback.
· It updates the actuator limits in the DMPC problem and may switch to a backup actuator (if available) or rely on neighboring tiles for cooling.
· The supervisor may reduce the energy budget for that tile and redistribute resources.

Power Loss:

· The supercapacitor provides a few seconds of power to complete the current control cycle and send a distress signal to the supervisor.
· The tile enters a safe mode: actuators are set to their default states (e.g., transpiration off, microchannel pump at minimum, VEM at high emissivity).

Communication Loss (Blackout):

· During blackout, the event‑triggering mechanism reduces transmissions; the supervisor may increase event thresholds to avoid unnecessary attempts.
· The switched ISS analysis (Theorem 7.2) guarantees that the system remains stable for bounded blackout intervals.
· After blackout ends, the supervisor resynchronizes the network by broadcasting a global state estimate.

---

9.6 Software Architecture

The embedded software is built on a real‑time operating system (RTEMS) to ensure deterministic timing. The control loop runs at 10 Hz, with the following tasks (priorities from highest to lowest):

1. Sensor Acquisition (priority 1): Read sensors, apply calibration, update local state.
2. Communication (priority 2): Send/receive CAN messages, update neighbor state buffers.
3. Control Computation (priority 3): Run accelerated ADMM for at most 10 iterations; use the first control input.
4. Health Monitoring (priority 4): Check actuator status, update fault flags.
5. Supervisor Interface (priority 5): Send status reports, receive commands.

The ADMM algorithm is implemented in C with optimized linear algebra libraries. The local MPC subproblem (quadratic program) is solved using an active‑set method with warm‑start from the previous solution.

