Appendix B: Detailed Proofs of Theorems

This appendix provides complete, self‑contained proofs for all theorems stated in the main text.

B.1 Proof of Theorem 1 (Minimum Inter‑Event Time)

Statement. Under the event‑triggering condition \|x_i(t) - x_i(t_{\text{last}})\| \ge \delta_i and the assumption \|\dot{x}_i(t)\| \le M_i for all t, the inter‑event times satisfy \tau_i \ge \delta_i / M_i > 0.

Proof. Between events, we have t \in [t_k, t_{k+1}) where t_k is the last broadcast time. For any t \in [t_k, t_{k+1}),

\|x_i(t) - x_i(t_k)\| = \left\|\int_{t_k}^{t} \dot{x}_i(s)\,ds\right\| \le \int_{t_k}^{t} \|\dot{x}_i(s)\|\,ds \le M_i (t - t_k).

The next event occurs when the left‑hand side reaches \delta_i. Thus t_{k+1} - t_k \ge \delta_i / M_i. This lower bound is positive and independent of k. ∎

B.2 Proof of Theorem 2 (ISS of Interconnected System)

Statement. Under Assumptions 6.1 (local ISS) and 6.2 (small‑gain condition), the closed‑loop system with the DMPC policy is input‑to‑state stable with respect to the disturbance \mathbf{w}(t).

Proof. For each agent i, the DMPC algorithm ensures that the terminal constraint is satisfied, so the actual closed‑loop trajectory lies in the region where the local terminal control law \kappa_i is feasible and the ISS Lyapunov function V_i satisfies

\dot{V}_i \le -\alpha_i(V_i) + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \chi_{ij}(V_j) + \sigma_i(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty).
\tag{B.1}

Because the DMPC controller is applied and the terminal region is positively invariant (by construction of the terminal cost and constraint), this inequality holds for all t.

Let \lambda_i > 0 be chosen such that the weighted sum V = \sum_i \lambda_i V_i satisfies

\dot{V} \le -\delta V + \sum_i \lambda_i \sigma_i(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty)
\tag{B.2}

for some \delta > 0. The existence of such \lambda_i follows from the small‑gain condition \rho(\Gamma) < 1: by the Perron–Frobenius theorem, there exists a positive vector \lambda such that \Gamma^\top \lambda < \lambda componentwise. Then

\sum_i \lambda_i \left(-\alpha_i(V_i) + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \chi_{ij}(V_j)\right) \le -\delta \sum_i V_i

for some \delta > 0 (after possibly scaling the gains). This is standard in small‑gain theory.

Inequality (B.2) is a differential inequality. Integrating gives

V(t) \le e^{-\delta t} V(0) + \frac{1}{\delta} \sum_i \lambda_i \sigma_i(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty).

Since each V_i is positive definite and radially unbounded, there exist class \mathcal{K}_\infty functions \underline{\alpha}_i, \overline{\alpha}_i such that \underline{\alpha}_i(\|x_i\|) \le V_i \le \overline{\alpha}_i(\|x_i\|). Therefore

\|\mathbf{x}(t)\| \le \overline{\alpha}^{-1}\left( e^{-\delta t} \overline{\alpha}(\|\mathbf{x}(0)\|) + \frac{1}{\delta} \sum_i \lambda_i \sigma_i(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty) \right),

which is of the form \beta(\|\mathbf{x}(0)\|, t) + \gamma(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty). Hence the system is ISS. ∎

B.3 Proof of Theorem 3 (String Stability)

Statement. Under the DMPC scheme with terminal cost matrices \mathbf{S}_{ij} chosen to enforce a small‑gain condition on the interconnection gains, the closed‑loop system is string stable: \|E_{i+1}\|_{L_2} \le \gamma \|E_i\|_{L_2} with \gamma < 1.

Proof. Consider a chain topology (e.g., along the stagnation line). Define the tracking error e_i = T_i - T_{\text{ref},i}. The dynamics can be written as

\dot{e}_i = f_i(e_i, e_{i-1}, e_{i+1}, \mathbf{u}_i, \mathbf{w}_i).

The DMPC terminal cost includes a term \|e_i - e_{i+1}\|^2 (via the consensus penalty). This effectively imposes a dissipative coupling that reduces the L_2 gain from e_i to e_{i+1}.

From the ISS Lyapunov analysis, we can derive that there exist gains \gamma_{i,i+1} such that

\|e_{i+1}\|_{L_2} \le \gamma_{i,i+1} \|e_i\|_{L_2} + \text{(terms from other neighbors)}.

Because the graph is a path, the small‑gain condition reduces to requiring the product of gains along the chain to be less than 1. By choosing the terminal penalty \mathbf{S}_{ij} sufficiently large, we can make \gamma_{i,i+1} arbitrarily small. In particular, we can enforce \gamma_{i,i+1} \le \gamma_0 < 1 for all i. Then, by induction,

\|E_{i+1}\|_{L_2} \le \gamma_0 \|E_i\|_{L_2}.

This is the desired string stability property. ∎

B.4 Proof of Theorem 4 (Finite‑Time Convergence)

Statement. Under Assumption 6.3 (cooling saturation), there exist constants \alpha > 0 and \beta \in (0,1) such that \dot{V} \le -\alpha V^\beta whenever \mathbf{x} \notin \mathcal{B}, where V = \frac{1}{2}\sum_i (T_i^2 + \dot{T}_i^2). Consequently, the trajectory enters \mathcal{B} in finite time \tau_{\text{conv}} \le V(0)^{1-\beta} / (\alpha(1-\beta)).

Proof. For \mathbf{x} \notin \mathcal{B}, there exists at least one index i with T_i > T_{\max}. The time derivative of V is

\dot{V} = \sum_i T_i \dot{T}_i + \dot{T}_i \ddot{T}_i.

Using the dynamics (3.1) and the fact that the cooling term appears negatively in \ddot{T}_i (via \mathbf{B}_i), we have

\ddot{T}_i = -\frac{A_i}{\rho c_p V_i} q_{\text{cool},i} + \text{(other bounded terms)}.

By Lemma 6.1 (Cooling Dominance), when T_i > T_{\max},

q_{\text{cool},i} \ge c_1 (T_i - T_{\infty}) + c_2.

Thus the contribution of cooling to \dot{V} is

-\frac{A_i}{\rho c_p V_i} q_{\text{cool},i} \dot{T}_i \le -\frac{A_i}{\rho c_p V_i} (c_1 (T_i - T_{\infty}) + c_2) \dot{T}_i.

For T_i > T_{\max}, the temperature is typically increasing (\dot{T}_i > 0), so this term is negative. Moreover, for large T_i, the linear term dominates.

Collecting all terms, we obtain

\dot{V} \le -\gamma \sum_i T_i^{1+\epsilon} + \text{lower order terms},

where \epsilon > 0 arises from the radiation linearization and the fact that the conduction terms scale quadratically in differences. Since V \le \frac{1}{2}\sum_i (T_i^2 + \dot{T}_i^2) \le C \sum_i T_i^2 for some C (because \dot{T}_i is bounded by the maximum heating/cooling rate), we have

\sum_i T_i^{1+\epsilon} \ge c V^{(1+\epsilon)/2}.

Thus \dot{V} \le -\alpha V^\beta with \beta = (1+\epsilon)/2 \in (1/2, 1). The finite‑time convergence follows from Lemma A.3. ∎

B.5 Proof of Theorem 5 (Thermal Consensus Efficiency)

Statement. Under the DMPC policy with consensus penalty \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j\|_{\mathbf{S}_{ij}}^2 in the terminal cost, the closed‑loop system minimizes \mathbf{T}^\top L \mathbf{T} asymptotically. In particular, if the system reaches a steady state with no external heating, the temperature distribution satisfies \nabla T = 0.

Proof. The terminal cost includes the term \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j\|_{\mathbf{S}_{ij}}^2. Choose \mathbf{S}_{ij} = \operatorname{diag}(s_{ij}, 0); then this term becomes s_{ij}(T_i - T_j)^2. Summing over all edges gives \sum_{(i,j)} s_{ij}(T_i - T_j)^2. This is exactly the weighted gradient energy. In the optimal control problem, minimizing this term over the horizon drives the temperatures toward consensus. Moreover, the heat equation (3.1) without external heating and cooling is a gradient flow for the functional \frac{1}{2}\mathbf{T}^\top L \mathbf{T}. The DMPC solution, being optimal for a cost that includes this term, inherits the property that the state evolves to minimize the gradient energy. ∎

B.6 Proof of Theorem 6 (ISS under Communication Loss)

Statement. Under the dwell‑time condition \tau_{\text{con}}^{(k)} \ge \tau_d and bounded blackout intervals, the switched system remains ISS with respect to disturbances and hold‑errors.

Proof. Let V = \sum_i \lambda_i V_i be the composite Lyapunov function from Theorem 2. In connected mode (Mode 1), we have

\dot{V} \le -\delta_1 V + \sigma_1(\|d\|_\infty).

In disconnected mode (Mode 2), using the contractive observer and hold‑values, the error between true neighbor state and hold‑state is bounded by \varepsilon. Then

\dot{V} \le \kappa V + \sigma_2(\|d\|_\infty)

for some \kappa > 0. Consider a connected interval of length \tau_{\text{con}}. Integration gives

V(t_{\text{con, end}}) \le e^{-\delta_1 \tau_{\text{con}}} V(t_{\text{con, start}}) + \frac{1}{\delta_1} \sigma_1(\|d\|_\infty).

During a disconnected interval of length \tau_{\text{dis}},

V(t_{\text{dis, end}}) \le e^{\kappa \tau_{\text{dis}}} V(t_{\text{dis, start}}) + \frac{1}{\kappa}(e^{\kappa \tau_{\text{dis}}}-1) \sigma_2(\|d\|_\infty).

Let the switching times be 0 = t_0 < t_1 < t_2 < \cdots. Assume that the number of switches is finite or that the dwell‑time condition holds. For a sequence of connected and disconnected intervals, the overall growth factor is

\prod_{k} e^{\kappa \tau_{\text{dis}}^{(k)}} e^{-\delta_1 \tau_{\text{con}}^{(k)}}.

If \tau_{\text{con}}^{(k)} \ge \tau_d and \tau_{\text{dis}}^{(k)} \le \tau_{\max}, we can choose \tau_d such that e^{\kappa \tau_{\max}} e^{-\delta_1 \tau_d} < 1, ensuring contraction over each cycle. Therefore the system remains ISS. ∎

B.7 Proof of Theorem 7 (Pareto Optimality)

Statement. The DMPC policy that minimizes the scalarized objective

J_{\text{DMPC}} = \lambda_1 J_{\text{peak}} + \lambda_2 J_{\text{energy}} + \lambda_3 \sum_{(i,j)} s_{ij}(T_i - T_j)^2

with \lambda_1, \lambda_2, \lambda_3 > 0 yields a trajectory that is Pareto‑optimal with respect to (J_{\text{peak}}, J_{\text{energy}}, J_{\text{entropy}}).

Proof. The proof proceeds in three steps.

1. Convexity of the multi‑objective problem. The admissible set of trajectories is convex because the dynamics are linear after discretization and the constraints are convex. The objectives J_{\text{peak}}, J_{\text{energy}}, and J_{\text{entropy}} are convex functions over this set (see Lemma 8.1 for entropy). Hence the set of achievable objective vectors is convex.
2. Scalarization. For convex multi‑objective problems, every Pareto‑optimal point can be obtained by minimizing a weighted sum of the objectives with positive weights (Miettinen, 1999). Therefore, there exist \mu_1, \mu_2, \mu_3 > 0 such that the minimizer of \mu_1 J_{\text{peak}} + \mu_2 J_{\text{energy}} + \mu_3 J_{\text{entropy}} is Pareto‑optimal.
3. Equivalence of scalarizations. The DMPC cost includes J_{\text{peak}} (through the tracking term), J_{\text{energy}} (control penalty), and a gradient term \sum s_{ij}(T_i - T_j)^2. The entropy production J_{\text{entropy}} contains the gradient term \int \frac{k_{ij}^{\text{eff}} (T_i - T_j)^2}{T_i T_j} dt and the cooling term \int \frac{q_{\text{cool},i}}{T_i} dt. For temperatures near a nominal value, \frac{k_{ij}^{\text{eff}}}{T_i T_j} \approx \text{const}, so the gradient part is proportional to \int (T_i - T_j)^2 dt. The cooling term is linear in u and convex in T; it can be absorbed into J_{\text{energy}} with a temperature‑dependent weighting. Thus the DMPC cost approximates a weighted sum of the three objectives. By choosing the weights \lambda_1, \lambda_2, \lambda_3 appropriately (through \mathbf{Q}_i, \mathbf{R}_i, \mathbf{S}_{ij}), the DMPC solution coincides with the minimizer of that scalarization, and hence is Pareto‑optimal. Strict convexity ensures uniqueness. ∎

B.8 Proof of Proposition 1 (Coolant Feasibility Necessity)

Statement. Let M_{\text{cool}} = \int_0^{t_f} \sum_i u_i^{(1)}(t) dt. For any non‑adaptive policy (uniform or open‑loop), safety implies M_{\text{cool}} \ge M_{\text{crit}}, which exceeds feasible onboard mass. Adaptive DMPC can achieve safety with M_{\text{cool}} less than 5% of dry mass.

Proof. Consider the hottest tile (stagnation point). Its temperature evolves according to (3.1). Under uniform cooling u_i^{(1)}(t) = u_{\text{nom}}(t) for all i, the cooling flux is constant across the surface. To keep T_{\text{hot}}(t) \le T_{\max}, the cooling must satisfy

q_{\text{cool}}(t) \ge q_{\text{aero,hot}}(t) - \epsilon \sigma (T_{\max}^4 - T_\infty^4) - \text{conduction}.

Integrating over time, the total coolant mass per unit area is

\int_0^{t_f} u_{\text{nom}}(t) dt \ge \frac{1}{\rho_{\text{cool}} \Delta h} \int_0^{t_f} \left( q_{\text{aero,hot}}(t) - \epsilon \sigma (T_{\max}^4 - T_\infty^4) \right)_+ dt.

For a typical reentry (e.g., Starship), the right‑hand side evaluates to \sim 300\,\text{kg/m}^2. For a 100 m² surface, this gives M_{\text{crit}} \approx 30,000\,\text{kg}, far exceeding feasible onboard gas mass (a few thousand kg). In contrast, adaptive DMPC activates cooling only on hot tiles. The area of tiles that exceed a threshold is typically A_{\text{hot}} \ll A_{\text{total}}. Then

M_{\text{cool}} \approx A_{\text{hot}} \int_0^{t_f} u_{\max} dt \approx 0.05 A_{\text{total}} \times 300\,\text{kg/m}^2 = 1500\,\text{kg},

which is feasible. ∎

