Appendix F: Additional Mathematical Derivations

This appendix contains detailed derivations of the discretized thermal dynamics, entropy production, linearization of radiation, and the decoupled HJI reachability.

F.1 Derivation of the Discretized Thermal Dynamics

Starting from the PDE:

\rho c_p \frac{\partial T}{\partial t} = \nabla \cdot (k\nabla T) + q_{\text{aero}} - \nabla \cdot q_{\text{cool}} - q_{\text{rad}}.

Using finite volumes with cell i of volume V_i, the left‑hand side becomes \rho c_p V_i \dot{T}_i. The conductive term is approximated by

\int_{\Omega_i} \nabla \cdot (k\nabla T) dV \approx \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \frac{k_{ij}(T_j - T_i)}{d_{ij}} A_{ij},

where d_{ij} is the distance between cell centers and A_{ij} the interface area. Define k_{ij} = (k_i + k_j)/2. The cooling term is

\int_{\Omega_i} \nabla \cdot q_{\text{cool}} dV \approx A_i q_{\text{cool},i},

where q_{\text{cool},i} is the net cooling flux from the actuators. The radiative term is A_i \epsilon_i \sigma (T_i^4 - T_\infty^4). Dividing by \rho c_p V_i yields the semi‑discrete equation:

\dot{T}_i = \frac{1}{\rho c_p V_i} \left[ \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \frac{k_{ij} A_{ij}}{d_{ij}} (T_j - T_i) + A_i q_{\text{aero},i} - A_i q_{\text{cool},i} - A_i \epsilon_i \sigma (T_i^4 - T_\infty^4) \right].

Define k_{ij}^{\text{eff}} = \frac{k_{ij} A_{ij}}{\rho c_p V_i d_{ij}}. Then

\dot{T}_i = \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} k_{ij}^{\text{eff}} (T_j - T_i) + \frac{A_i}{\rho c_p V_i} q_{\text{aero},i} - \frac{A_i}{\rho c_p V_i} q_{\text{cool},i} - \frac{A_i \epsilon_i \sigma}{\rho c_p V_i} (T_i^4 - T_\infty^4).

Differentiating yields the second‑order form used in the main text.

F.2 Derivation of Entropy Production

The entropy balance for a control volume is:

\frac{dS}{dt} = \int_{\partial V} \frac{\mathbf{q}}{T} \cdot \mathbf{n} \, dA + \int_V \frac{\dot{q}_{\text{gen}}}{T} \, dV + \dot{S}_{\text{gen}},

where \dot{S}_{\text{gen}} \ge 0 is the entropy production rate. For the thermal subsystem, using the heat equation, one can show that

\dot{S}_{\text{gen}} = \int_V \frac{k}{T^2} \|\nabla T\|^2 \, dV + \int_V \frac{(q_{\text{aero}} - \nabla\cdot q_{\text{cool}})}{T} \, dV - \int_{\partial V} \frac{q_{\text{rad}}}{T} \, dA.

After discretization, the conductive term becomes \sum_{(i,j)} \frac{k_{ij}^{\text{eff}} (T_i - T_j)^2}{T_i T_j}. The cooling term becomes \sum_i \frac{A_i q_{\text{cool},i}}{T_i}. The radiation term becomes \sum_i \frac{A_i \epsilon_i \sigma (T_i^4 - T_\infty^4)}{T_i}. Summing gives the expression in the main text.

F.3 Linearization of the Radiation Term

The radiation flux q_{\text{rad}} = \epsilon \sigma (T^4 - T_\infty^4) is linearized around T_0 as:

q_{\text{rad}} \approx \epsilon \sigma (4T_0^3 (T - T_0) + T_0^4 - T_\infty^4).

Thus in the linearized dynamics, the contribution to the \dot{T}_i equation is -\frac{A_i \epsilon_i \sigma 4T_{i0}^3}{\rho c_p V_i} (T_i - T_{i0}), which adds a term to the state matrix \mathbf{A}_i.

F.4 Decoupled HJI Reachability

For a single agent with dynamics \dot{x} = f(x,u) + d, where d \in \mathcal{D} is a bounded disturbance, the HJI PDE for safety x \in \mathcal{S} reduces to a Hamilton–Jacobi–Bellman equation. When the disturbance is treated as a bounded set, the value function can be computed via level‑set methods. For the decoupled approximation, we solve the 2‑dimensional HJI for each tile with d taken as the worst‑case coupling from neighbors (bounded by \bar{d}). The resulting BRS for the decoupled system is a subset of the true BRS, providing a conservative safety certificate.

